00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:28.565
Even if you normally would have

40
00:01:28.565 --> 00:01:32.240
a UI type of environment
to work with,

41
00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:36.700
in Linux, often when
you have a problem,

42
00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:39.740
you might not have the
option to use the UI.

43
00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:41.990
The problem might happen
early in a boot sequence

44
00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:44.720
before you're able to
load a UI, for instance.

45
00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.170
Again, command line becomes
the least common denominator

46
00:01:48.170 --> 00:01:51.740
of what's available at

47
00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:54.350
a given point anytime
we're booting the system.

48
00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:56.570
It's often just the
easiest, fastest,

49
00:01:56.570 --> 00:01:59.830
and the most reliable way to
remotely access the system.

50
00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:02.060
There's other ways to set up so

51
00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:04.400
that you can get access
to the full UI remotely.

